				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Cha, whats a good amount <a name="14407"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 5 04 12:05 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Here's an email I sent on the subject (maybe to the same person, not sure)...
<br />

<br />
That is a good question. One bards have been asking themselves since the game started.  SoE has been essentially mum on the topic of what the bard's primary stats are, unlike those of melees or casters, we are forced to look to the equipment SoE gives us for keys to what stats are considered primary.  That being said, CHA is considered to be one of the bard's attributes that should get some attention.  To answer your question, below is a recap of the uses of CHA.
<br />
 
<br />
CHA, aside from the obvious vendor selling/buying benefits (caping at 130-135), works to a certain degree in both lull, mez/charm and missed notes.  When lulling a mob, your CHA has nothing to do with your success or resist (only the instrument mod and your level compared to that of the mob's do).  However,  in the event of a resist, a check is made against your CHA.  If it succeeds, nothing happens and you can re-lull the mob.  If the check fails, you get a critical failure and that mob and all his friends in close proximity (social range) come after you, even some that you previously lulled if their reduced range is breached.  You most likely will be using Level 8 Lull to pull in LDoN or other groups in your 50s and 60s, and the fewer adds you bring back the better as you will likely be performing Crowd Control (CC) as well.  For this reason, I always ask for a CHA buff from the shammy/chanter if one is available before I start pulling.  Every little bit helps.
<br />
 
<br />
CHA supposedly impacts mezing and charming as well, but all I can say here is that your use of an instrument and your level in relation to the mob's have a much larger impact on your success of mezing charming, as well as, the length of your charm (early breaks are no fun).  For this reason, when I was gheavily swarm kiting in my early 50s, I had a set of CHA gear to help land charm, but using my flute was a bigger help.
<br />
 
<br />
For missed notes, several bards have parsed their missed notes at different levels of CHA, and have determined there to be limited benefit from CHA.  From memory, the results were something like no benefit from 100 to 200 cha, limited benefit at 255 and a decent benefit at 305.  Note you can only get pas 255 with Planar Power or something like that, which requires you be in the early-mid 60s.  From those testings, it is pretty obvious that unless SoE changed things and didn't tell us, missed notes are here to stay and there's really nothing the average bard can do about them.
<br />
 
<br />
All that being said, where should your CHA be in the 50s and 60s?  Well, mine is currently at 140 unbuffed in melee mode at 64.  Essentially I have ignored CHA and went for STA instead (taking the inevitable hit is more imporant to me than a few resists).  That being said, I normally roll for CHA augments from LDoN and put them on my gear, especially since I'm never in a group where I am not asked to pull anymore.  I make up for my woeful CHA by asking for CHA buffs, but honestly, I haven't seen a great difference between 140 and 200.  I still get a critical failure about once a week.
<br />
 
<br />
So, my opinion... you should not purposefully drop your CHA, via wearing an item that has good stats, but negative CHA (like Crustaesian sp? armor) in yor 50s. But if you are like me and following Sapper's formula for determining gear upgrades (see the guides section for more info), you notice CHA is not on the list.  HPs are everything as you get up there in levels.  You WILL be pulling and you WILL take 1-5 hits by mobs before your tanks can grab aggro.  For mobs doing 500+ damage a hit you see where HPs are a must.
<br />
 
<br />
Sinfonian
<br />

<br />
P.S. Scambon, that's a good test, but just make sure you use your flute to charm.  You will get resisted far more with 200 CHA and no flute than you will with 120 CHA and a decent flute.  At least you should, I have not tested it as I sold all my CHA gear. <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />  - Sinf.</span></td>
