				<td colspan="2"><span>I have 167 CHA and last night did a hard LDoN, but got no lull resists.  The only time I though I got one was when I was actually singing the wrong song! <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-10.gif" border="0" alt="Blushing" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
However, I suspect that your level must come into the resist calculations for lulls.  I was level 50 at the time, the highest was 51 and we had a couple of 44s, so the average level was a couple of levels below me.  I've done other hard LDoNs where resists are much more common.
<br />

<br />
I also didn't get many more mez resists than normal, and used charm several times, which surprised the cleric who said I wouldn't be able to successfully mez on a hard mission! <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-4.gif" border="0" alt="Tongue out" hspace="2" />
<br />

<br />
<i>EDIT: I lie!  I got one critical lull resist on a named, which was the last fight of the adventure (but, we kicked its a$$, with the help of a little charming and mezzing, so CHA saves the day again!).</i>
<br />

<br />
<i>EDIT 2: It has been pointed out elsewhere (by my munificent guild leader, Klapton/Scherzo) that an additional MR debuff from equipping a wind instrument makes more difference to charm duration than CHA.  I was not equipping my flute on this adventure, which I don't always have the time for mid-battle, so in this case CHA may have been the deciding factor in my crowd control efforts.  I was charming quite a bit, and didn't notice any particularly early breaks.</i></span></td>
